Apple Earnings
--------------

From the Wall Street Journal ( https://www.wsj.com/tech/apple-earnings-q4-a=
apl-stock-8552e5b6 ) :

Apple reported revenue reached an all-time high for the September quarter, =
propelled by a modest rebound in iPhone sales that came ahead of its releas=
e of new artificial-intelligence tools. For Apple=E2=80=99s fiscal fourth q=
uarter, total sales were $94.9 billion, beating the $94.5 billion analysts =
were expecting, according to FactSet. Net income fell around 35% to $14.7 b=
illion due to a judicial ruling in Europe that will force Apple to pay more=
 than $14 billion in taxes to Ireland. Apple shares were down nearly 2% in =
after-hours trading. The company said it expects revenue in the December qu=
arter to grow in the low- to mid-single digits. Analyst projections for sal=
es growth in that period are 6.6%, according to FactSet.

This was, at first glance, a very boring set of results; I was tempted to s=
kip them given I am already a week behind. A closer consideration, though, =
suggests that it is the boringness that is itself interesting.

AI, Capex, and R&D
------------------

First, there is the fact that Apple, unlike the rest of its Big Tech brethr=
en, does not have any increases in capital expenditure to report. Note this=
 bit from (outgoing) CFO Luca Maestri in the Q&A portion of the earnings ca=
ll ( https://sixcolors.com/post/2024/10/this-is-tim-apples-q4-results-phone=
-call-transcribed/ ) :

*Could you just talk a little bit about the CapEx outlook and whether inves=
tments in things like Private Cloud Compute could change the historical Cap=
Ex range of roughly $10 billion a year.*

On the CapEx front, I=E2=80=99ve mentioned before a number of times, we hav=
e a bit of a hybrid model in the way we run our data centers. In some cases=
, we use our own data centers, in some cases we use third-party providers, =
and so our CapEx numbers may not be fully comparable with others. But obvio=
usly we are rolling out these Apple Intelligence features already now, and =
so we are making all the capacity that is needed available for these featur=
es. You will see in our 10K the amount of CapEx that we=E2=80=99ve incurred=
 during the course of fiscal =E2=80=9924, and we will in fiscal =E2=80=9925=
 continue to make all the investments that are necessary, and of course, in=
vestments in AI-related CapEx will be made.

One of the advantages of waiting to write about these earnings is that Appl=
e=E2=80=99s 10-K is now out ( https://s2.q4cdn.com/470004039/files/doc_earn=
ings/2024/q4/filing/10-Q4-2024-As-Filed.pdf ) , and not only are capital ex=
penditures not up, they are actually the second lowest they have been in th=
e last ten years; only COVID-impacted 2020 was lower:

Now Apple does, as Maestri noted, rent a lot of their computing capacity, w=
hich goes into some combination of their Cost of Services and Cost of Produ=
ct; still, given that margins are higher than ever, there clearly isn=E2=80=
=99t some sort of major shift happening there either. Apple=E2=80=99s finan=
cials reflect the vision the company painted at WWDC; I wrote in an Update =
( https://stratechery.com/2024/wwdc-apple-intelligence-apple-aggregates-ai/=
?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9=
ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiL=
CJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHRwczovL3N0=
cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDI0L3d3ZGMtYXBwbGUtaW50ZWxsaWdlbmNlLWFwcGxlLWFnZ3JlZ2F=
