BNnkEZ1ye4sVM0hXFawUjmOfF7KGytwdIQTgIPgHWS9PCaocboFlafIXtdaqTLHDwcmOR7VyQKO=
t1TB4hMoMVaRBTIx4cSfmWfy0jitrblSzShkEFzUm35PZyRvi8OujykYVAsZT9OKVYfvzS0ooB-=
6a20-bwcbngNv6Q ) :

Apple is positioning itself as an AI Aggregator: the company owns users and=
, by extension, generative AI demand by virtue of owning its platforms, and=
 it is deepening its moat through Apple Intelligence, which only Apple can =
do; that demand is then being brought to bear on suppliers who probably hav=
e to eat the costs of getting privileged access to Apple=E2=80=99s userbase=
=E2=80=A6

Apple, probably more than any other company, deeply understands its positio=
n in the value chains in which it operates, and brings that position to bea=
r to get other companies to serve its interests on its terms; we see it wit=
h developers, we see it with carriers, we see it with music labels, and now=
 I think we see it with AI. Apple =E2=80=94 assuming it delivers on what it=
 showed with Apple Intelligence =E2=80=94 is promising to deliver features =
only it can deliver, and in the process lock-in its ability to compel partn=
ers to invest heavily in features it has no interest in developing but want=
s to make available to Apple=E2=80=99s users on Apple=E2=80=99s terms.

It does still seem that we should see some amount of capital expenditure in=
crease for Apple=E2=80=99s Private Compute Cloud; perhaps Apple is simply r=
enting more cloud capacity and using its existing data centers for that Pri=
vate Compute Cloud as it waits for its custom M4 server chips ( https://asi=
a.nikkei.com/Business/Technology/Tech-Asia/Apple-asks-Foxconn-to-produce-se=
rvers-in-Taiwan-in-AI-push ). Regardless, Apple has always been different t=
han other tech companies for a whole host of reasons; here is another major=
 difference to add to the list!

That noted, while Apple Intelligence primarily runs on device, it does requ=
ire R&D. Here=E2=80=99s Maestri answering another question about that line =
item:

*Given how much your tech peers are spending on AI, does this new era of Ap=
ple Intelligence actually require Apple to invest more in R&D beyond your c=
urrent 7 to 8 percent of sales to capture this opportunity?*

Krish, as you know, we=E2=80=99ve been investing heavily in R&D over the la=
st several years. Our R&D growth has been significant during the last sever=
al years. And obviously as we move through the course of fiscal =E2=80=9924=
, we=E2=80=99ve also reallocated some of the existing resources to this new=
 technology, to AI, and so the level of intensity that we=E2=80=99re puttin=
g into AI has increased a lot and you maybe don=E2=80=99t see the full exte=
nt of it because we=E2=80=99ve also had some internal reallocation of the b=
ase of engineering resources that we have within the company.

Yes, R&D has been increasing in absolute terms, but it has actually stayed =
relatively stable in terms of percent of sales:

This doesn=E2=80=99t necessarily mean the company hasn=E2=80=99t responded =
to generative AI; Maestri=E2=80=99s comment about =E2=80=9Csome internal re=
allocation of the base of engineering resources=E2=80=9D reminds me of this=
 Bloomberg story ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-02-27/apple=
-cancels-work-on-electric-car-shifts-team-to-generative-ai ) from earlier t=
his year:

Apple Inc. is canceling a decadelong effort to build an electric car, accor=
ding to people with knowledge of the matter, abandoning one of the most amb=
itious projects in the history of the company. Apple made the disclosure in=
ternally Tuesday, surprising the nearly 2,000 employees working on the proj=
ect, said the people, who asked not to be identified because the announceme=
nt wasn=E2=80=99t public. The decision was shared by Chief Operating Office=
r Jeff Williams and Kevin Lynch, a vice president in charge of the effort, =
according to the people.

The two executives told staffers that the project will begin winding down a=
nd that many employees on the car team =E2=80=94 known as the Special Proje=
cts Group, or SPG =E2=80=94 will be shifted to the artificial intelligence =
division under executive John Giannandrea. Those employees will focus on ge=
nerative AI projects, an increasingly key priority for the company.

Apple is, at the end of the day, a very disciplined company; look no furthe=
r than the last few years, where revenue growth has flatlined, which means =
R&D growth has flatlined as well. And, when it came time to invest in AI, A=
pple didn=E2=80=99t up its spending, but rather re-allocated it. It=E2=80=
=99s also worth remembering that Apple, despite its massive size, is still =
a relatively simple company with simple product lines, that does best when =
it focuses on one thing at a time; that focus is clearly AI, which for Appl=
e, means giving up on other speculative projects like an Apple car.

There is one more angle to the Apple AI story that ties these two pieces to=
gether: Apple Intelligence is free, which is to say there is no indication =
that it will drive incremental revenue. That is a good reason to limit mass=
ive capex increases! What Apple Intelligence might do is drive iPhone upgra=
des; that, though, will result in higher revenue, which as we=E2=80=99ve se=
en, will be the lever to unlocking more R&D spend.

Of course this could all go sideways, if in fact it turns out to be importa=
nt for Apple to own its own leading edge model, and they find themselves ye=
ars behind. They could, however, almost certainly buy their way into the ga=
me if they had to, or (gulp) cut a deal with Meta. For now the early iPhone=
 16 results suggest their cautious approach is warranted: yes, there was a =
decent little increase over last year, but it is notable that, once again, =
the 16 Pro appears to be outselling the regular 16. In other words, Apple=
